  "doc_id": "45234",
  "text": "Any benefits of capping in reducing the variability of an index may not be present in participants with more advanced disease. Future refinement of the capping process must take into account the need to be able to utilize the procedure in eyes at different stages of the disease and/or with coexisting ocular pathologies. An alternative approach to reducing the effect of variability in near-normal regions of the visual field could be to use testing algorithms based on the linear scale instead of SITA standard, so that measurement errors in these regions (when expressed in linear units) are no longer disproportionately large when compared to those at damaged locations. It is possible that this could reduce or remove the benefits of using capped global indices. More likely, it would improve the predictability of linear-based indices by reducing their variability. Due to this issue, any benefits of using the new indices described in this paper over the established indices may be underestimated. A linear staircase testing algorithm has been described [CITATION_1] , and further work extending this concept is warranted.",
  "correct_citation": {
